"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135011","Department for International Development","false","2019-07-03","<p>Each year snakebites kill more than 80,000 people and at least 450,000 people are thought to suffer life-changing injuries such as loss of limbs and permanent disability.</p><p>There are major technical challenges for the production and distribution of anti-venoms in low- and middle-income countries, including lack of quality anti-venoms, high cost of anti-venoms, poor regulation, poor distribution policies and marketing of inappropriate or poor-quality anti-venoms.</p><p>DFID recently launched a £9 million Research programme to develop new snakebite treatments which will be effective against multiple species, affordable, stable in tropical temperatures and easy to use in local communities, to overcome some of the distribution challenges.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-07-03T15:58:06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135011/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135011/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-06-26","Developing Countries: Antivenom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of work to support the distribution of snake anti-venom products in developing countries; and whether his Department supports any such project.","false","Biography information for George Eustice","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","269701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135012","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-05","<p>The information requested can be found in the table below.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Table: Number of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) cases disallowed at initial decision for failing the PIP assessment in 2018, and the number of those who subsequently completed the Mandatory Reconsideration (MR) process, Great Britain</strong></p><p /><p><em> </em></p><p><em> </em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em>-</em></p></td><td><p>Number of PIP Cases</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PIP cases disallowed at initial decision after completing the PIP assessment</p></td><td><p>216,850</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>A) </em><em>Of Which:</em> Subsequently Completed an MR</p></td><td><p>105,430</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>B) </em><em>Of Which:</em> Had the Initial Decision to Disallow Revised at MR</p></td><td><p>12,480</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em> </em></p><p><em>Source: PIP Computer System.</em></p><p><em>Data has been rounded to the nearest 10.</em></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>PIP data includes normal rules and special rules for the terminally ill claimants, and is for both new claims and DLA reassessment claims.</p><p> </p><p>MR data is up to March 2019.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-07-05T12:21:17.017Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135012/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135012/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-06-26","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications for the personal independence payment were refused on the first assessment in 2018; and how many of those applications that were refused were subsequently (a) considered again and (b) granted under Mandatory Reconsideration.","false","Biography information for George Eustice","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","269702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135013","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-01","<p>The Department continues to support awareness of Group B streptococcus, alongside the wider international community.</p><p>Group B streptococcus is the leading cause of bacterial infection in newborn babies. The Government has recognised there are gaps in the evidence relating to this issue and the National Institute for Health Research has commissioned a trial to compare the clinical and cost effectiveness of universal screening compared with usual risk-based care, which will help to understand more about the potential benefits and harms of this approach.</p><p>This is a large-scale and ambitious trial, the results of which will be of interest to the United Kingdom National Screening Committee and will form one piece of the developing evidence picture to inform its future recommendations for screening for Group B streptococcus.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-07-01T15:15:23.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135013/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135013/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-06-26","Streptococcus: Health Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether the Government will recognise July as International Group B Strep Awareness Month; and what progress has been made on improving (a) prevention and (b) awareness of group B streptococcus .","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","269598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135014","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-07-04","<p>Rigorous statistical analysis, which adjusts for differences related to the risk of TB in cattle, has been carried out to measure any association between badger culling and cattle TB incidence in comparison to areas where badger culling has not taken place. This analysis covers data from four years of culling in Areas 1 and 2 (Gloucestershire and Somerset), and two years of culling in Area 3 (Dorset), and has been submitted to a peer-review journal.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2019-07-04T13:34:14.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135014/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135014/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-06-26","Bovine Tuberculosis: Disease Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has for a peer-reviewed analysis of the effectiveness of badger culling in reducing the incidence of Bovine Tuberculosis in cattle herds in areas where badger culling schemes has been running for three years or more.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","269824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135015","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-05","<p>DWP is committed to providing the best possible support for all our claimants, including the most vulnerable in society. We are continuously reviewing and improving the service for vulnerable people to ensure that it is accessible and responsive to their needs.</p><p> </p><p>Specific training and guidance is provided for all staff on working with different vulnerable groups. This includes developing the skills they need to support and communicate with a diverse range of customers.</p><p> </p><p>All DWP staff have access to the ‘Safeguarding Vulnerable People’ guidance, which highlights the importance of having arrangements in place which assist in the protection of vulnerable adults and children from physical abuse, sexual abuse and exploitation.</p><p> </p><p>To assist with identification and claimant support, each Jobcentre Plus site has a complex needs toolkit in place and these are maintained and reviewed locally.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, Jobcentre staff have access to a District Provision Tool which provides access to the full range of provision and support delivered by DWP, providers, local authorities and independent volunteer/charity organisations. However, if Work Coaches are unable to identify local provisions that meets the needs of the claimant, they liaise with DWP Partnership Managers, who have the flexibility to work alongside local organisations to source appropriate provision helping our most vulnerable, at risk, claimants to access the support they need.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We have also been closely engaging with key stakeholders on a range of topics and we will continue to work closely with them on improving our services, policies and support for victims of abuse.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-07-05T12:58:36.547Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135015/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135015/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-06-26","Sexual Offences: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what training and guidance her Department provides to Jobcentre Plus Work Coaches and other staff in her Department on (a) the specific vulnerabilities of women at risk of, or experiencing, sexual exploitation and (b) specialist services that staff may refer to that support women to exit prostitution.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","269825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135016","Home Office","false","2019-07-08","<p>The Government's priority is to protect those selling sex from harm and exploitation and target those who exploit vulnerable people involved in prostitution. We believe that people who want to leave prostitution should be given every opportunity to find routes out. We continue to work closely with the police, Crown Prosecution Service, other front-line agencies and wider partners to ensure the legislation achieves these aims.</p><p>We have provided over £2m to organisations supporting sex workers, including £650,000 from the Violence Against Women and Girls Service Transformation Fund to Merseyside PCC, to provide a victim-focused service for sex workers who are victims, or at risk of sexual or domestic violence and abuse, exploitation or human trafficking.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-07-08T15:36:17.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135016/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135016/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-06-26","Prostitution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Home Department, what steps he has taken to commission specialist services that aim to support women to exit prostitution and enter the workplace.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","269826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135017","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-07-01","<p>The full clinical history of recruits is considered. This includes smoking and family history, taking account of cardiovascular diseases and stroke. Recruits also receive a full clinical examination.</p><p>In addition to this, Army recruits have an electrocardiogram and, when clinically indicated, a transthoracic cardiac echo is performed. This screening is designed to detect significant structural and electrophysiological abnormalities.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2019-07-01T13:50:50.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135017/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135017/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-06-26","Armed Forces: Heart Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what her Department's policy is on screening new recruits to identify the risk of sudden cardiac death.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","269662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135018","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-01","<p>The Department holds no information on the number of clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) which follow the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) 2017 guideline, NG77.</p><p> </p><p>NICE clinical guidelines are based on a thorough assessment of the available evidence and are developed through engagement with stakeholders. They represent best practice and CCGs are expected to take them fully into account when planning and commissioning high-quality services healthcare services that meet the needs of their local population, including cataract surgery.</p><p>NHS England is responsible for holding CCGs to account to ensure they are commissioning services that meet the needs of their local populations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","269607","2019-07-01T15:46:19.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135018/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135018/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-06-26","Cataracts: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information the Department holds on the number of NHS Clinical Commissioning Groups that follow the NICE 2017 guideline, NG77, on cataract surgery.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","269606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135019","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-01","<p>In the last five years there has only been one instance of Network Rail issuing a Certificate of Lawfulness for entry to a tenanted railway arch and that was in London. In this instance it was an emergency entry without prior consent by the Department for Transport, who were subsequently notified and raised no objections.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-07-01T13:12:09.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135019/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135019/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-06-26","Network Rail: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many times his Department has issued a Certificate of Lawfulness to Network Rail for entry to a tenanted railway arch under section 14 of the Railway Regulation Act 1842 in the last five years in (a) London and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","269827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135020","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-01","<p>The Department holds no information on the number of clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) which follow the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) 2017 guideline, NG77.</p><p> </p><p>NICE clinical guidelines are based on a thorough assessment of the available evidence and are developed through engagement with stakeholders. They represent best practice and CCGs are expected to take them fully into account when planning and commissioning high-quality services healthcare services that meet the needs of their local population, including cataract surgery.</p><p>NHS England is responsible for holding CCGs to account to ensure they are commissioning services that meet the needs of their local populations.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","269606","2019-07-01T15:46:19.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135020/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135020/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-06-26","Cataracts: Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to promote best practice across Clinical Commissioning Groups on the NICE 2017 guideline, NG77, on cataract surgery.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","269607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135021","Treasury","false","2019-07-02","<p>Departments have been commissioned to carry out the work necessary for a 3-year Spending Review concluding this Autumn.</p><p> </p><p>However, it will be for the new Government to decide whether the circumstances make it appropriate to conduct a full 3-year Spending Review, or a single year exercise.</p><p> </p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2019-07-02T15:13:07.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135021/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135021/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-06-26","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to launch a three-year spending review before the summer recess; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","269828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135022","Treasury","false","2019-07-02","<p>HM Treasury is working with the Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government to support the financial sustainability of local councils, so they can continue to offer a range of vital services to their local authorities.</p><p> </p><p>Departments have been commissioned to carry out the work necessary for a 3-year Spending Review concluding this Autumn.</p><p> </p><p>However, it will be for the new Government to decide whether the circumstances make it appropriate to conduct a full 3-year Spending Review, or a single year exercise.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2019-07-02T15:10:56.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135022/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135022/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-06-26","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for financial planning by local authorities of the uncertainty of the timing of the next spending review.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","269829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135023","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-01","<p>We are not aware of any test carried out in the EU on High Pressure Laminates panels since June 2017 other than the tests the Government is currently undertaking.</p><p>The Department is aware that manufacturers routinely carry out fire safety tests of their products but is not automatically made aware of these.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2019-07-01T15:20:50.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135023/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135023/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-26","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department is aware of any large-scale fire tests carried out in other EU Member States on High Pressure Laminate cladding since June 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","269830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135024","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-01","<p>In summer 2017, the Department asked Building Research Establishment (BRE) to contact all of their customers to ask them to publish information about large scale tests. BRE contacted their customers who had tested and achieved BR 135 classifications for their external cladding systems. Where permission to publish details of a cladding system has been granted, the BRE produced a database which summarises the generic components included within the successfully tested cladding systems. The data base is available at the following: <a href="https://gbr01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bre.co.uk%2Fregulatory-testing&amp;data=02%7C01%7CCharles-Elie.Romeyer%40communities.gov.uk%7C197206014b1b499f27f708d6fbc3519f%7Cbf3468109c7d43dea87224a2ef3995a8%7C0%7C0%7C636973213638804895&amp;sdata=jRS2yIRqDq%2FUTii11618SWq2%2B9ZZbwyrJkfx23H33es%3D&amp;reserved=0" target="_blank">https://www.bre.co.uk/regulatory-testing</a></p><p>In addition the Department is aware that a number of product manufacturers have voluntarily made this information available on their websites.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","269832","2019-07-01T15:19:10.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135024/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135024/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-26","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has asked private manufacturers to disclose the large-scale fire tests they have carried out on High Pressure Laminate cladding since June 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","269831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135025","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-07-01","<p>In summer 2017, the Department asked Building Research Establishment (BRE) to contact all of their customers to ask them to publish information about large scale tests. BRE contacted their customers who had tested and achieved BR 135 classifications for their external cladding systems. Where permission to publish details of a cladding system has been granted, the BRE produced a database which summarises the generic components included within the successfully tested cladding systems. The data base is available at the following: <a href="https://gbr01.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bre.co.uk%2Fregulatory-testing&amp;data=02%7C01%7CCharles-Elie.Romeyer%40communities.gov.uk%7C197206014b1b499f27f708d6fbc3519f%7Cbf3468109c7d43dea87224a2ef3995a8%7C0%7C0%7C636973213638804895&amp;sdata=jRS2yIRqDq%2FUTii11618SWq2%2B9ZZbwyrJkfx23H33es%3D&amp;reserved=0" target="_blank">https://www.bre.co.uk/regulatory-testing</a></p><p>In addition the Department is aware that a number of product manufacturers have voluntarily made this information available on their websites.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","269831","2019-07-01T15:19:10.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135025/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135025/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-06-26","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has asked manufacturers of High Pressure Laminate cladding to disclose the result of large-scale fire tests they have carried out on High-Pressure Laminate cladding since 2005.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","269832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135026","Department for Education","false","2019-07-01","<p>Between 2017-18 and the end of May 2019, the department has spent £69 million on pre-opening start-up grants to support local authority schools to convert to become academies. This includes the conversion of failing local authority schools to become sponsored academies in order to improve pupil outcomes. In addition, further capital costs are incurred for some cases where the fabric of school buildings has not been sufficiently well maintained.</p><p>Further details can be found in in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Spend </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>£38 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>£30 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019-20 (as at end of May 2019)</p></td><td><p>£1 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£69 million</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Future years’ spending plans have yet to be determined and will form part of the next Spending Review.</p><p>Academy status leads to a more dynamic and responsive education system by allowing schools to make decisions based on local need and the interests of their pupils.</p><p>My right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education, is required by legislation to intervene in underperforming maintained schools rated inadequate by Ofsted and to issue an academy order for the school to become a sponsored academy. Recent research found that sponsored academies, particularly those open longest, have made substantial gains in performance in comparison with similar non-academy schools. The latest figures show that over 7 out of 10 sponsored academies are good or outstanding, replacing schools that were mostly underperforming. 85% of children are now in good or outstanding schools, compared to just 66% in 2010, and this is in part down to our reforms.</p><p>Where academies choose to come together in academy trusts, they can take advantage of economies of scale and drive down the costs of procurement and so are able to invest more in teaching. By working in partnership with each other, schools can benefit from sharing staff, curriculum expertise and effective pedagogy.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-01T16:59:13.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135026/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135026/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-06-26","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding his Department has spent or plans to spend on converting schools to academies in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21, (e) 2021-22, (f) 2022-23 and (g) 2023-24.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","269833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135027","Department for Education","false","2019-07-02","<p>The Resource DEL total expenditure disclosed as ‘Other Resource’ in the department’s annual report and accounts 2017-18 is £18,897 million. This expenditure applies to the department’s estimate lines as set out in the table below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Estimate Row 2017-18</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount (in millions of pounds)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Activities to Support all Functions</p></td><td><p>-23*</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>School Infrastructure and Funding of Education (Department)</p></td><td><p>81</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>School Infrastructure and Funding of Education (ALB) (Net)</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Education Standards, Curriculum and Qualifications (Department)</p></td><td><p>69</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Social Care, Mobility and Equalities (Department)</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Social Care, Mobility and Equalities (ALB) (Net)</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Standards and Testing Agency</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National College for Teaching and Leadership</p></td><td><p>40</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA)</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Grants to LA Schools via ESFA</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Grants to Academies via ESFA</p></td><td><p>18,617</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Higher Education</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Further Education</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Higher Education (ALB) (net)</p></td><td><p>57</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Further Education (ALB) (net)</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total Resource DEL defined as &quot;Other Resource&quot; in 2017-18 Data Tables</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>18,894**</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>*The amount in ‘Activities to Support All Functions’ is shown as a negative figure, as it represents net income (ie income is greater than expenditure for ‘Other Resource’ on this row in the table above).</p><p>**The table total differs from the published ‘Other Resource’ figure by approximately £3 million due to audit adjustments which have not been allocated to any one estimate line.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2019-07-02T16:39:18.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135027/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135027/answer","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135027/answer/previousversion/126282","Biography information for Anne Milton","60","Education","Education","2019-06-26","Department for Education: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 25 June 2019 to Question 267289, which programmes have been funded within the budget lines provided in that Answer; and how much funding has been (a) allocated to and (b) spent by each programme.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","269834"
