"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135029","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-07-01","<p>Algorithmic tools are used both by the National Probation Service and Community Rehabilitation Companies to support decision making and aid professional judgement in assessing the level of risk posed by offenders. We have internal processes in place to ensure we develop and roll-out algorithmic models appropriately and responsibly and are working with The Alan Turing Institute to make sure the use of these models is ethical, safe and fair. These tools are one element of a number of measures for assessing the risk of re-offending: In all cases, the professional judgement of the offender manager is a key factor in deciding what measures are needed to manage an offender and prevent re-offending.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2019-07-01T16:46:45.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135029/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135029/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-06-26","Probation: Artificial Intelligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent discussions his Department has had with (a) community rehabilitation companies and (b) the Probation Service on the use of algorithms in the probation system.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","269689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135030","Home Office","false","2019-07-01","<p>The Home Office has regular discussions with Police and Crime Commissioners across a wide range of issues.</p><p>We recognise the potential that the use of emerging technologies present in the Criminal Justice System for improving outcomes for citizens and also the importance of ensuring that these are used in a way which is compliant with appropriate legal and ethical frameworks. We welcome the work by the Centre for Data Ethics and Innovation (CDEI) to develop a code of practice for use of algorithms in predictive policing and will be working with them to develop it.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2019-07-01T15:55:14.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135030/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135030/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-06-26","Criminal Proceedings: Artificial Intelligence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions he has had with Police and Crime Commissioners in England and Wales on the use of algorithms in the criminal justice system.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","269690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135031","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-07-02","<p>Officials from the Ministry of Defence and the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy have been involved in discussions at desk level regarding our approach to the UK Steel charter.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2019-07-02T12:37:03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135031/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1135031/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-06-26","Ministry of Defence: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether her Department has had discussions with the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on the UK Steel charter.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","269724"
